CONSULT-31 / OPUS — CPU soft-skin tail-spike mechanism analysis
================================================================
File: src/engine/client/library/clientSkeletalAnimation/src/shared/appearance/
      SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp
Construction: ~1297-1384   Consumption (no-dot3 path): ~1903-1937
Math: sharedMath/src/shared/Transform.h rotateTranslate_l2p (lines 463-469)

GIVENS (treated as proven, not re-derived):
- Tail-contiguous spike: last ~27 verts of a 1656-vert mesh (1629..1655); second
  mesh 2628 verts, tail starts ~2575. CONTIGUOUS TAIL is the load-bearing clue.
- Wrong cluster ~[-2816, 0, -6400], Y EXACTLY 0. Correct bulk ~[3400, 5, -4900].
- Dest VB fully written. Every bone index used is IN RANGE (runtime clamp = 0 fires).
- High-LOD only. Low-LOD clean.
- blendPos = Σ_k transformArray[idx_k].rotateTranslate_l2p(srcPos) * weight_k.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE DECISIVE STRUCTURAL FACT
----------------------------------------------------------------------
`transformData` (the m_transformData cursor) is ONE shared running pointer for the
WHOLE mesh, advanced per-vertex by m_extraTransformDataCount:

   const TransformData *transformData = m_transformData;            // 1846/1099/887
   for (i ...) {
       ... firstTransform ...
       for (j = sourceVectors->m_extraTransformDataCount; j>0; j--, transformData++)
           ... transformArray[transformData->m_transformIndex] ...  // 1927-1936
   }

There is NO per-vertex reset of `transformData`. It is a stream cursor. The j-loop
trusts each vertex's m_extraTransformDataCount to consume EXACTLY the right number
of TransformData slots. The construction packs m_transformData as a tightly-packed
stream: vertex v contributes (localCount-1) entries ONLY when localCount>1 (1304-1307
sizing; 1375-1380 fill).

=> If ANY single vertex's m_extraTransformDataCount does not match the number of
   slots that vertex actually contributed to the packed stream, the cursor desyncs
   by that delta and STAYS desynced for EVERY following vertex. The first verts read
   correct stream entries; once the cursor slips, the remainder read SHIFTED entries
   — i.e. valid TransformData (valid indices, real weights) belonging to the WRONG
   vertex. This is EXACTLY a "contiguous tail goes wrong, head stays correct, indices
   all in range" signature. No other candidate mechanism naturally produces a
   sharp head/tail boundary from one defect.

WHERE THE COUNT CAN BE WRONG — the localVertexTransformCount<1 branch (1359-1363):
   if (localVertexTransformCount<1) {
       sourceVertex.m_firstTransformData.m_transformIndex  = 0;
       sourceVertex.m_firstTransformData.m_transformWeight = 0;
       // m_extraTransformDataCount NOT set here -> relies on memset-0 (1316)
   }
This branch leaves m_extraTransformDataCount = 0 (memset). That is actually SAFE for
the cursor (count 0 == 0 slots contributed). So the <1 branch is NOT itself the
desync source under normal data.

The REAL desync risk is the asymmetry between the SIZING pass and the FILL pass:
  - SIZING (1300-1308) and FILL (1340-1381) both call mesh.getVertexTransformCount().
  - They must return the IDENTICAL value for every vertex across the two passes.
  - High-LOD meshes have the densest, most-weighted verts (3-4 bones/vert). If a
    high-LOD vertex returns localCount>1 in fill (so it sets m_extraTransformDataCount
    = localCount-1 AND advances destTransformData) but the two passes ever diverge —
    OR if a vertex with localCount>1 but a malformed weight table writes fewer real
    slots than counted — destTransformData ends up != numberOfExtraTransformWeightPairs.
  - That mismatch is exactly what the WARNING at 1384 guards. CHECK THAT WARNING:
    if it ever fired for these meshes, the cursor math is broken and the tail is
    guaranteed garbage. (Low-LOD meshes have fewer multi-bone verts -> smaller/zero
    extra stream -> no room to desync -> CLEAN. This explains high-LOD-ONLY directly.)

----------------------------------------------------------------------
WHY Y == EXACTLY 0 (the strongest discriminator)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
rotateTranslate_l2p (Transform.h 463-469):
   x' = m00*x + m01*y + m02*z + m03
   y' = m10*x + m11*y + m12*z + m13
   z' = m20*x + m21*y + m22*z + m23
Then blendPos = Σ_k transform_k(src) * weight_k.

For the FINAL blendPos.y to be EXACTLY 0.0f (bitwise zero, not ~0), one of:
 (A) Σ weight_k == 0 for the tail vert. Then blendPos = src-transformed * 0 = (0,0,0)
     for ALL three components — but target X,Z are large (-2816,-6400), NOT zero.
     So a pure zero-weight-sum is FALSIFIED by X,Z != 0. REJECT.
 (B) The dominant transform contributing to the tail vert has its MIDDLE ROW zero:
     m10=m11=m12=m13=0. Then y' = 0 exactly for any src, while x',z' are nonzero.
     A PoseModelTransform whose row 1 is all-zero is NOT a normal animated bone
     pose (those are orthonormal-ish, |row|≈1). It IS what you get from:
        - a partially-initialized / zeroed matrix where only some rows were written,
        - reading a TransformData entry that points (via desync) at a bone the pose
          left as a degenerate/zero-row matrix at a valid index,
        - reading PAST the logical end of a per-vertex contribution into a slot that
          was memset-0 then never filled (the 1316 memset leaves zero matrices).
 (C) A genuine projection/flatten in the bone matrix (designer-zeroed scale on Y).
     Possible but would affect ALL LODs equally -> contradicts high-LOD-only. REJECT.

(B) is the winner and it DOVETAILS with the cursor-desync: a desynced cursor that
runs off the packed stream lands in the trailing memset-0 region of m_sourceData
(alloc_size was sized to numberOfExtraTransformWeightPairs exactly; running past it
reads zero-initialized bytes -> TransformData{index=0, weight=0} OR, if it reads
transformArray via a 0 index, transformArray[0] which may be the ROOT/identity-ish
pose). Critically, reading transformData PAST m_transformData's valid region yields
m_transformWeight bytes that are 0 (memset) => those extra terms add 0; the vert then
equals firstTransform(src)*firstWeight. If firstWeight itself got corrupted, or the
single surviving transform is a near-zero-row matrix, you collapse Y while X,Z ride
the m03/m23 translation columns of that bone -> [bigX, 0, bigZ]. That is the observed
[-2816, 0, -6400] shape: a TRANSLATION-DOMINATED result (src rotated to ~0 on Y,
offset by a bone whose position column sits near that cluster).

ARITHMETIC SANITY on [-2816,0,-6400]: this is NOT a linear scaling of [3400,5,-4900]
(no single scalar maps 3400->-2816 AND -4900->-6400; ratios -0.828 vs +1.306 differ
and Y 5->0 needs a separate zero). So it is NOT "correct vertex times a bad weight
sum". It IS "src mapped through a DIFFERENT bone matrix" — consistent with reading
the wrong (desynced) TransformData / a zero-row pose, whose translation columns place
the result at the bone's own anchor near [-2816,*,-6400]. Confirm by checking whether
some bone in transformArray has position ≈ [-2816, 0, -6400]: if yes, the tail verts
are being skinned ENTIRELY to that one bone (weight collapse onto a single foreign
bone via desync), which also forces Y≈that bone's anchor — and if that bone's row-1
is degenerate, Y locks to exactly 0.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
RANKED MECHANISMS (by fit)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. CURSOR DESYNC (m_extraTransformDataCount / packed-stream miscount), tail reads
   shifted-or-past-end TransformData. UNIQUELY explains: contiguous-tail boundary,
   head-correct, valid-in-range indices, full write, high-LOD-only (denser extra
   stream = more desync room). Y=0 emerges from landing on a zero-row / memset-0
   /single-foreign-bone term. *** BEST FIT. ***
2. STALE/DEGENERATE POSE AT A VALID INDEX (bone allocated, not animated this frame ->
   zero-row or identity matrix). Explains Y=0 cleanly and in-range indices, but does
   NOT by itself explain the sharp tail-only boundary unless paired with desync (the
   tail is what gets routed onto that one bad bone). Strong as the Y=0 PROXIMATE
   cause, weak as the standalone trigger. Likely the *value* half of mechanism 1.
3. LOD index→bone-table remap mismatch (high-LOD stored indices vs runtime pose
   table). Explains high-LOD-only and in-range-but-wrong indices, but would scatter
   errors across the whole mesh, NOT a clean contiguous tail. Lower fit.
4. Weight-sum != 1 / sign error. FALSIFIED for the pure case: cannot produce
   Y-exactly-0 while X,Z stay large (a scalar hits all 3 axes). Only survives if the
   "extra" weights are the memset-0 tail (sum<1) AND the surviving bone is degenerate
   — which is just mechanism 1 again. Reject as a standalone.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE ONE CONFIRMING EXPERIMENT
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Instrument the consumption loop to detect cursor desync DIRECTLY, not the symptom:
Before the i-loop, save base = m_transformData. After the loop, assert
(transformData - m_transformData) == numberOfExtraTransformWeightPairs — i.e. the
cursor consumed EXACTLY the stream length. BETTER (localizes the slip): inside the
loop, before each vertex, log i and (transformData - m_transformData); ALSO compute a
parallel "expected offset" by summing m_extraTransformDataCount as you go and the
independent count = Σ over verts of max(localTransformCount-1,0) recomputed from the
mesh. The FIRST i where (running m_extraTransformDataCount sum) diverges from (running
mesh-derived extra count) is the desync vertex; every i after it is the spike tail.
Equivalently and cheapest: re-enable/inspect the WARNING at line 1384
(destTransformData - m_transformData != numberOfExtraTransformWeightPairs). If that
fires for the 1656/2628 meshes, mechanism 1 is PROVEN. As a second confirm, at the
first spiked tail vertex dump transformArray[idx].getPosition() and matrix row 1
([m10..m13]) for the dominant bone — expect position ≈ [-2816,*,-6400] and/or a
zero/degenerate row 1 (Y collapse).
